WEBVTT

00:05.506 --> 00:07.174
<i>[rock music]</i>

00:07.174 --> 00:09.760
<i>- Tonight, we continue</i>
<i>our first-ever</i>

00:09.760 --> 00:12.638
"Forged in Fire"
invitational tournament.

00:12.638 --> 00:14.973
<i>Over five weeks,</i>
<i>four classes</i>

00:14.973 --> 00:17.976
<i>of metalsmithing</i>
<i>professionals, farriers,</i>

00:17.976 --> 00:20.896
<i>armorers, blacksmiths,</i>
<i>and modern metalworkers</i>

00:20.896 --> 00:24.191
<i>will put their blademaking</i>
<i>skills to the test.</i>

00:24.191 --> 00:27.194
It's the first time where
all four of our bladesmiths

00:27.194 --> 00:30.155
<i>come from a similar</i>
<i>metalworking class.</i>

00:30.155 --> 00:32.741
<i>The winner from each class</i>
<i>will go head to head</i>

00:32.741 --> 00:34.826
<i>for a chance at the title</i>
<i>of tournament champion</i>

00:34.826 --> 00:37.204
<i>and the biggest purse ever.</i>

00:37.204 --> 00:38.539
$50,000.

00:38.539 --> 00:40.582
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:40.582 --> 00:44.253
<i>Right now, round three</i>
<i>belongs to the blacksmiths.</i>

00:44.253 --> 00:47.798
<i>Four blacksmiths bring their</i>
<i>unique skills to the Forge.</i>

00:47.798 --> 00:49.424
- Blacksmiths are the
all-around,

00:49.424 --> 00:52.010
all-purpose metalworkers.

00:52.010 --> 00:54.888
<i>- To compete for the honor</i>
<i>of representing their class</i>

00:54.888 --> 00:58.350
<i>in the "Forged in Fire"</i>
<i>Tournament of Champions.</i>

00:58.350 --> 01:01.311
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

01:01.311 --> 01:08.110
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:08.110 --> 01:09.903
<i>- I am Derick Kemper.</i>

01:09.903 --> 01:12.114
I got started in blacksmithing
in high school.

01:12.114 --> 01:14.992
I wanted to learn all of it.
I wanted to be a farrier.

01:14.992 --> 01:16.743
I wanted to do
ornamental smithing,

01:16.743 --> 01:19.830
<i>and I wanted to do</i>
<i>knife-making, of course,</i>

01:19.830 --> 01:21.707
because every teenage boy
wants to make knives.

01:21.707 --> 01:24.167
[laughs]

01:24.167 --> 01:27.170
- My name is Karl Dunn.
If I see something and like it,

01:27.170 --> 01:30.632
<i>whether it be</i>
<i>hooks, tools, knives,</i>

01:30.632 --> 01:33.010
I feel compelled
to try and make it.

01:33.010 --> 01:36.430
<i>Why buy it for $30</i>
<i>when you can make it for 600?</i>

01:36.430 --> 01:38.015
<i>- My name is</i>
<i>Charlie Carpenter.</i>

01:38.015 --> 01:40.559
I live just south
of St. Louis, Missouri.

01:40.559 --> 01:43.854
<i>My grandfather was basically</i>
<i>the town blacksmith,</i>

01:43.854 --> 01:46.148
and my dad has always
kind of tinkered with it.

01:46.148 --> 01:48.191
<i>So blacksmithing</i>
<i>and bladesmithing</i>

01:48.191 --> 01:50.485
<i>was just kind of</i>
<i>the next logical step for me.</i>

01:50.485 --> 01:52.070
<i>- My name is Tony Rhode.</i>

01:52.070 --> 01:53.697
I was a landscaper
for many years.

01:53.697 --> 01:55.449
<i>Then, I had a back injury</i>

01:55.449 --> 01:57.451
<i>that didn't allow me</i>
<i>to do that anymore.</i>

01:57.451 --> 01:59.244
<i>My résumé used to read:</i>

01:59.244 --> 02:01.621
"Might not be smart,
but I can sure lift a lot."

02:01.621 --> 02:03.332
Now, my résumé reads:

02:03.332 --> 02:05.125
"Still not smart,
and now I can't lift a lot."

02:05.125 --> 02:06.376
[chuckles]

02:06.376 --> 02:08.503
<i>So I started making knives.</i>

02:08.503 --> 02:11.214
- Blacksmiths,
welcome to our first ever

02:11.214 --> 02:14.051
"Forged in Fire"
invitational tournament.

02:14.051 --> 02:16.845
Today, you blacksmiths
will have to survive

02:16.845 --> 02:19.431
a competition in three rounds
that is specifically designed

02:19.431 --> 02:22.225
to test every aspect of your
bladesmithing capabilities.

02:22.225 --> 02:24.269
You'll have to compete
against one another

02:24.269 --> 02:27.314
to earn a spot
at the blacksmith's anvil

02:27.314 --> 02:29.733
in our invitational
Tournament of Champions

02:29.733 --> 02:32.069
all in front of our panel
of expert judges.

02:32.069 --> 02:35.947
Up first, two-time "Forged
in Fire" champion Ben Abbott.

02:35.947 --> 02:39.201
Historic weapons re-creation
specialist David Baker.

02:39.201 --> 02:42.913
Edged weapon specialist
Doug Marcaida.

02:42.913 --> 02:46.375
Gentleman, you'll need every
tool in your toolbox to win.

02:46.375 --> 02:48.960
Plus, maybe some of these.

02:48.960 --> 02:52.089
- Just as he's grabbing
that thing, the anticipation.

02:52.089 --> 02:53.965
<i>It's like,</i>
<i>what's it going to be?</i>

02:53.965 --> 02:57.052
It's a car, it's crap from
somebody's garden shed.

02:57.052 --> 02:59.971
<i>[dramatic musical flourish]</i>

02:59.971 --> 03:01.932
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:01.932 --> 03:04.685
- Some tools from our toolbox.

03:04.685 --> 03:07.854
- And it's like...Okay.

03:07.854 --> 03:13.485
Take a breath, look at it,
pick something, and go.

03:13.485 --> 03:15.779
- You'll have to harvest steel
from these tools

03:15.779 --> 03:18.699
to forge signature
Damascus blades.

03:18.699 --> 03:22.119
<i>Your blades must have</i>
<i>a drop point, through tang,</i>

03:22.119 --> 03:24.579
<i>and have an edge between</i>
<i>12 and 15 inches</i>

03:24.579 --> 03:27.124
<i>as measured from tip</i>
<i>to plunge grind.</i>

03:27.124 --> 03:28.959
And in the second round,
you'll be attaching handles

03:28.959 --> 03:31.586
to those blades to turn them
into fully functioning weapons

03:31.586 --> 03:33.588
that will be tested
for strength and durability

03:33.588 --> 03:35.966
in a fire brick chop,

03:35.966 --> 03:40.303
and for edge retention
in a grinder belt slice.

03:40.303 --> 03:42.305
You will have ten minutes
to work on your designs.

03:42.305 --> 03:45.142
You will have three hours
to forge your blades.

03:45.142 --> 03:48.812
And one more thing.
You'll be using these.

03:48.812 --> 03:50.730
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

03:50.730 --> 03:53.358
This is a 2-inch by 2-inch can.

03:53.358 --> 03:55.444
<i>- Aw, crap.</i>

03:55.444 --> 03:57.446
I've only been monkeying
with canister

03:57.446 --> 04:01.074
for a month or two,
and a 2 by 2 cube

04:01.074 --> 04:04.453
<i>is not sufficient</i>
<i>to make a blade this large,</i>

04:04.453 --> 04:05.829
so automatically, I know, well,

04:05.829 --> 04:08.123
it's going to take
two or three.

04:08.123 --> 04:10.959
- Good luck, bladesmiths.

04:10.959 --> 04:13.336
Your ten-minute design window
starts now.

04:13.336 --> 04:15.046
<i>[rock music]</i>

04:15.046 --> 04:16.923
These blacksmiths have to make

04:16.923 --> 04:20.469
drop point through tang
Damascus blades.

04:20.469 --> 04:22.846
What is a drop point, exactly?

04:22.846 --> 04:24.723
- Drop point is where
the top of your knife,

04:24.723 --> 04:27.642
towards the point,
comes down and meets the point.

04:27.642 --> 04:29.686
- They tend
not to be symmetrical.

04:29.686 --> 04:32.898
Like a spear point,
it's symmetrical.

04:32.898 --> 04:35.859
Whereas the drop point
tends to have a cutting edge,

04:35.859 --> 04:38.820
and then the top
sort of gently drops--

04:38.820 --> 04:40.822
- Well, if you all pull knives,
I'll pull one out too.

04:40.822 --> 04:43.241
[laughter]

04:43.241 --> 04:46.453
- I'm going to make
some form of the Viking seax

04:46.453 --> 04:48.663
<i>because I love</i>
<i>Scandinavian culture.</i>

04:48.663 --> 04:51.124
<i>When you pick it up,</i>
<i>I want it to feel like</i>

04:51.124 --> 04:53.043
<i>it's actually</i>
<i>200 or 300 years old,</i>

04:53.043 --> 04:54.044
and it came from Scandinavia.

04:54.044 --> 04:56.296
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:56.296 --> 04:58.924
- I'm going to make just a drop
point camp knife, or something

04:58.924 --> 05:01.134
<i>that would handle what</i>
<i>they were going to do to it.</i>

05:01.134 --> 05:02.844
Being a blacksmith,
the advantage

05:02.844 --> 05:04.346
that it brings
to the competition, I think,

05:04.346 --> 05:07.599
is just the ability
to see the task at hand,

05:07.599 --> 05:10.769
and make the calculations on
what has to happen.

05:10.769 --> 05:12.938
- How many of those cubes
do you think it'll take

05:12.938 --> 05:16.233
to make a knife between
12 and 15 inches in length?

05:16.233 --> 05:18.985
- We always say "forge thick."
Use two cans.

05:18.985 --> 05:20.487
It's always good to have more

05:20.487 --> 05:21.988
so that you can
work your way down.

05:21.988 --> 05:23.448
<i>[upbeat music]</i>

05:23.448 --> 05:26.243
- I don't usually
draw my knives out,

05:26.243 --> 05:28.495
<i>so I just start doodling.</i>

05:28.495 --> 05:30.247
I might as well
doodle something

05:30.247 --> 05:32.207
<i>that looks like a chopper.</i>

05:32.207 --> 05:35.252
<i>I'm kind of going for almost</i>
<i>an axe-like edge on it</i>

05:35.252 --> 05:37.212
<i>than a knife-like edge,</i>

05:37.212 --> 05:40.549
just because I know it's going
to be bashed into bricks.

05:40.549 --> 05:43.885
- I'm going to be making
a drop point modified hunter.

05:43.885 --> 05:45.512
<i>It's got a slight recurve,</i>

05:45.512 --> 05:47.639
<i>so it'll be good</i>
<i>for the slicing.</i>

05:47.639 --> 05:49.307
<i>But it's got a lot of meat</i>
<i>in the spine,</i>

05:49.307 --> 05:51.810
so when they whack
at the brick, it'll do well.

05:51.810 --> 05:54.688
- Bladesmiths, this ten minute
design period is closed.

05:54.688 --> 05:58.441
Grab your steel, your three
hour forge time starts now.

05:58.441 --> 06:00.235
<i>[rock music]</i>

06:00.235 --> 06:02.696
Talk to me a little bit
about metal selection.

06:02.696 --> 06:05.031
- They should be grabbing
things that are easy

06:05.031 --> 06:08.618
to manipulate into the cubes.
Bits of chain, or fish hooks.

06:08.618 --> 06:11.288
Anything you can pack in there
rapidly and get to making.

06:11.288 --> 06:12.831
- I start by
grabbing the shovel.

06:12.831 --> 06:14.583
<i>It's thin material.</i>

06:14.583 --> 06:16.668
<i>It'll give me somewhat</i>
<i>of a pattern.</i>

06:16.668 --> 06:19.212
I'm going to see
what I can make work here.

06:19.212 --> 06:23.008
<i>- Derick has cut, it looks</i>
<i>like four separate slots</i>

06:23.008 --> 06:26.595
<i>up that shovel, and now,</i>
<i>he's dropping off pieces.</i>

06:26.595 --> 06:28.930
Actually a really
efficient way to do this.

06:28.930 --> 06:32.183
- Yeah, sure.
- This is only the second time

06:32.183 --> 06:34.728
I've really done
a canister-type weld.

06:34.728 --> 06:36.438
- Should they
be peeling the cans?

06:36.438 --> 06:38.356
Does it matter?
- Leave that can on,

06:38.356 --> 06:40.609
because, remember,
those cans are mild steel.

06:40.609 --> 06:45.113
- My plan is to make the cube
part of the blade.

06:45.113 --> 06:46.281
Because that way,
I don't have to fool

06:46.281 --> 06:48.533
with trying to get it off.

06:48.533 --> 06:50.785
<i>- I think that this spring</i>
<i>is going to go good for me</i>

06:50.785 --> 06:52.662
<i>because it's</i>
<i>a small enough spring</i>

06:52.662 --> 06:54.539
<i>that I can cut it into</i>
<i>small pieces pretty quickly,</i>

06:54.539 --> 06:56.041
get them cleaned up,

06:56.041 --> 06:57.542
and then get them
so they fit in the cube.

06:57.542 --> 06:59.461
- That coil spring,

06:59.461 --> 07:01.755
it's got a really thick coating
on the outside of it.

07:01.755 --> 07:04.215
I don't know if that's a paint.
<i>- All of a sudden,</i>

07:04.215 --> 07:06.259
it's taking me longer
than I thought it would.

07:06.259 --> 07:09.137
- There's other steel in there
that's more readily available.

07:09.137 --> 07:10.889
<i>[rock music]</i>

07:10.889 --> 07:13.683
- I'm using fish hooks,
because they're clean,

07:13.683 --> 07:15.477
they're small,
they'll fit in the can.

07:15.477 --> 07:17.395
<i>It's going to heat up quickly,</i>

07:17.395 --> 07:19.189
<i>because there's not</i>
<i>as much mass in the metal.</i>

07:19.189 --> 07:21.524
- Karl's got the liquid paper.

07:21.524 --> 07:23.234
He's coating the inside
of those canisters.

07:23.234 --> 07:24.402
Not a bad idea.

07:24.402 --> 07:26.071
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:26.071 --> 07:28.198
- The items that I
picked out of the pile

07:28.198 --> 07:31.910
<i>were the chisels and the rasp.</i>
<i>Those should be hardenable.</i>

07:31.910 --> 07:33.411
<i>Working on these cubes,</i>
<i>I mean,</i>

07:33.411 --> 07:35.288
it's the first time
I've ever done it.

07:35.288 --> 07:37.248
<i>But in the blacksmith shop,</i>
<i>you have to adapt</i>

07:37.248 --> 07:39.751
and try to figure it out
on the fly.

07:39.751 --> 07:41.586
I don't know how much
I can get out of a cube,

07:41.586 --> 07:43.713
<i>so I build three cubes.</i>

07:43.713 --> 07:46.675
But one of those has got
this volcano going on in there

07:46.675 --> 07:48.426
that I'm not comfortable with.

07:48.426 --> 07:50.261
- Is that that that
powdered steel burning up?

07:50.261 --> 07:52.430
- It is; there's some just
on the outside of the can,

07:52.430 --> 07:54.057
or there's a relatively
big hole in the can

07:54.057 --> 07:56.101
and the stuff is pouring out.

07:56.101 --> 07:58.103
- That is not good.

07:58.103 --> 08:02.065
I throw the thing to the floor
and keep going.

08:02.065 --> 08:03.733
- One hour has elapsed!

08:03.733 --> 08:06.778
You only have
two hours remaining!

08:06.778 --> 08:08.113
- Historically,
blacksmiths pretty much

08:08.113 --> 08:09.406
work with all kinds of metal,

08:09.406 --> 08:10.990
making so many
different things.

08:10.990 --> 08:12.951
But, no matter whether
you're a blacksmith,

08:12.951 --> 08:15.662
armorer, or a farrier,

08:15.662 --> 08:18.873
what matters is your skill
as a knife-maker.

08:18.873 --> 08:21.626
- I needed to cut the tops
off these two cans,

08:21.626 --> 08:23.920
<i>so that I can</i>
<i>forge weld them together.</i>

08:23.920 --> 08:27.006
Leaving as much of the jacket
as possible will save time,

08:27.006 --> 08:29.342
because I've seen
so many people struggle

08:29.342 --> 08:31.386
with trying to
get these cases off.

08:31.386 --> 08:32.887
Oh, yeah.

08:32.887 --> 08:34.681
<i>[rock music]</i>

08:34.681 --> 08:37.183
If I don't get these to
weld together properly,

08:37.183 --> 08:39.394
<i>I'm just going to have</i>
<i>a ruined bar of steel,</i>

08:39.394 --> 08:40.937
and that's it, I'm going home.

08:40.937 --> 08:43.565
- So it looks like Derick
has his cubes

08:43.565 --> 08:47.277
welded together end to end
like building blocks.

08:47.277 --> 08:49.738
- Smart, because remember,
he's got the canister material

08:49.738 --> 08:52.615
around the outside,
so if he cut off the ends,

08:52.615 --> 08:55.618
he can stack them upright,
and forge weld them that way.

08:55.618 --> 08:58.997
- Do you trust that weld?
- A solid weld is a solid weld.

08:58.997 --> 09:02.250
- I am really looking
to try to pay for my wedding.

09:02.250 --> 09:05.754
We postponed our wedding
for me to be able to do this.

09:05.754 --> 09:07.297
So, here we are.

09:07.297 --> 09:08.923
[laughs]

09:08.923 --> 09:10.592
<i>[rock music]</i>

09:10.592 --> 09:13.011
- I go to start
removing the canister.

09:13.011 --> 09:15.764
<i>It just does not</i>
<i>want to come off.</i>

09:15.764 --> 09:18.933
I haven't even addressed
the other can yet.

09:18.933 --> 09:22.937
<i>I decided I'm just going</i>
<i>to try to grind off one side,</i>

09:22.937 --> 09:24.814
<i>leave the mild steel on,</i>

09:24.814 --> 09:27.567
and expose enough
of the hardenable steel

09:27.567 --> 09:29.486
so I have a good cutting edge.

09:29.486 --> 09:30.904
It ain't going to be
my best work.

09:30.904 --> 09:32.781
- Tony just ground the can off

09:32.781 --> 09:34.699
the facets
with an angle grinder,

09:34.699 --> 09:36.659
and I think he's setting up
for a forge weld right now.

09:36.659 --> 09:39.204
- Nice, he'll have
a longer, thicker blade.

09:39.204 --> 09:40.830
More stuff to work with.

09:40.830 --> 09:42.457
<i>[rock music]</i>

09:42.457 --> 09:44.250
<i>- I abandoned one can because</i>

09:44.250 --> 09:46.169
it didn't feel like
it was welded up,

09:46.169 --> 09:48.838
so I've got these two
that are pretty solid steel.

09:48.838 --> 09:51.091
<i>I wasn't able to</i>
<i>get the cans off clean,</i>

09:51.091 --> 09:53.510
<i>so I'm going to weld them</i>
<i>together with the cans on.</i>

09:53.510 --> 09:55.053
<i>Hopefully, I can grind away</i>
<i>enough steel</i>

09:55.053 --> 09:56.888
<i>to reveal that good steel.</i>

09:56.888 --> 10:00.183
I'm feeling pretty good.
Heated it, fluxed it.

10:00.183 --> 10:02.852
I'm moving forward,
I'm forging the shape.

10:02.852 --> 10:05.897
- Karl is drawing that
blade out quite a bit.

10:05.897 --> 10:08.233
It looks good.
- Yeah, it does, too.

10:08.233 --> 10:12.487
- As I'm starting
to forge in the tip,

10:12.487 --> 10:15.323
<i>I notice that a couple</i>
<i>of the welds at the very end,</i>

10:15.323 --> 10:17.867
<i>they're starting to fold open.</i>

10:17.867 --> 10:21.037
I got to tell you,
I'm--I'm--I'm panicking.

10:21.037 --> 10:23.456
- Karl's doing these little
tippy-taps with his hammer,

10:23.456 --> 10:25.250
but that steel's
not hard enough to forge weld,

10:25.250 --> 10:26.751
so I don't really know
what he's doing.

10:26.751 --> 10:30.463
- Ah, it's not forged,
it's not set.

10:30.463 --> 10:33.091
- Maybe he was just trying
to close off a void.

10:33.091 --> 10:35.260
- It's not set.
- Karl's walking away

10:35.260 --> 10:38.680
from his forge,
sweating quite profusely.

10:38.680 --> 10:41.850
- If I can't figure out how to
get these things closed up

10:41.850 --> 10:43.685
or ground off, I'm going home.

10:47.564 --> 10:50.066
<i>- I notice that a couple of</i>
<i>the welds at the very end,</i>

10:50.066 --> 10:52.443
<i>they're starting to fold open.</i>

10:52.443 --> 10:54.904
I got to tell you,
I'm panicking.

10:54.904 --> 10:56.948
The weld's not set.

10:56.948 --> 10:59.325
Man, that clock is moving fast.

10:59.325 --> 11:00.785
<i>I've got to</i>
<i>get these things closed up,</i>

11:00.785 --> 11:02.954
or it'll just fail.

11:02.954 --> 11:05.582
<i>So I have to make</i>
<i>a quick decision,</i>

11:05.582 --> 11:07.250
rather than a perfect decision.

11:07.250 --> 11:09.627
- You got to be able to
problem solve on the fly.

11:09.627 --> 11:11.963
- So I decide to cut off
a quarter of an inch

11:11.963 --> 11:14.299
of that steel at the edge.

11:14.299 --> 11:17.218
<i>I'm just going to have to</i>
<i>forge the tip again.</i>

11:17.218 --> 11:18.887
<i>[rock music]</i>

11:18.887 --> 11:20.638
- Come on, Charlie.
It's so close.

11:20.638 --> 11:21.764
<i>- Getting that stupid canister</i>
<i>off of there</i>

11:21.764 --> 11:23.683
<i>is really putting me behind.</i>

11:23.683 --> 11:26.186
<i>I've got not much time</i>
<i>to get a billet made.</i>

11:26.186 --> 11:27.770
- You can start to see
all the frustration,

11:27.770 --> 11:29.772
because he feels like
he's behind.

11:29.772 --> 11:31.858
<i>- I can't get the damn thing</i>
<i>off of there,</i>

11:31.858 --> 11:34.110
so I just totally
gave up on it.

11:34.110 --> 11:37.655
<i>The clock is ticking,</i>
<i>and I've got to keep going.</i>

11:37.655 --> 11:39.240
- Charlie's second can

11:39.240 --> 11:41.534
is underneath
his forge over there.

11:41.534 --> 11:43.745
<i>- I've got one canister</i>
<i>at this point,</i>

11:43.745 --> 11:46.372
but I know there's nowhere
near enough material there

11:46.372 --> 11:48.791
to make a knife
to meet the parameters.

11:48.791 --> 11:51.002
So, I grab a leaf spring,

11:51.002 --> 11:54.047
<i>and then sandwich</i>
<i>those on either side.</i>

11:54.047 --> 11:56.633
The easy part is what
I've been doing so far.

11:56.633 --> 11:58.009
<i>And now, I've got</i>
<i>to start hammering,</i>

11:58.009 --> 11:59.886
or my ass is melting down.

11:59.886 --> 12:01.596
I got to start making something
that looks like a knife.

12:01.596 --> 12:02.764
<i>[rock music]</i>

12:02.764 --> 12:04.140
<i>- I've got a nice billet.</i>

12:04.140 --> 12:05.850
I know that
drawing out the blade

12:05.850 --> 12:07.393
is going to be my strong point.

12:07.393 --> 12:09.479
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:09.479 --> 12:12.357
- I like his hammer technique.
That's good to see.

12:12.357 --> 12:14.567
- Let's talk a little bit
about Derick's blade.

12:14.567 --> 12:16.778
With that curve,
when you're hitting a brick,

12:16.778 --> 12:18.863
it's only going to hit
in two places,

12:18.863 --> 12:21.783
leaving that curve
nice and sharp.

12:21.783 --> 12:23.534
Instead of having
a blade that's flat,

12:23.534 --> 12:26.204
and coming down flat,
and dulling the whole edge.

12:26.204 --> 12:27.789
It's kind of a genius design.

12:27.789 --> 12:30.166
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:30.166 --> 12:33.127
- At this point,
I'm jumping back and forth

12:33.127 --> 12:35.755
<i>between Big Blue</i>
<i>and the press,</i>

12:35.755 --> 12:37.799
<i>trying to do</i>
<i>as much as possible,</i>

12:37.799 --> 12:39.717
and to draw this beast out.

12:39.717 --> 12:42.303
- Tony needs to start
putting a bevel on his blade.

12:42.303 --> 12:43.346
- Yeah, I know, it's so thick.

12:43.346 --> 12:45.223
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:45.223 --> 12:48.810
<i>- The pressure is just about</i>
<i>getting to me.</i>

12:48.810 --> 12:51.187
I still need to
get my tang thinned out.

12:51.187 --> 12:53.856
<i>I know I need</i>
<i>to kick 'er up a notch.</i>

12:53.856 --> 12:54.899
- The preparation time
they took.

12:54.899 --> 12:56.359
They were very meticulous

12:56.359 --> 12:57.694
about their steel
and everything else,

12:57.694 --> 12:59.153
but it kind of
works against them

12:59.153 --> 13:00.446
when you're in
a timed competition.

13:00.446 --> 13:02.282
<i>[rock music]</i>

13:02.282 --> 13:05.618
- None of our smiths have
quenched their blades yet.

13:05.618 --> 13:08.997
I think that Karl
is heating up his oil.

13:08.997 --> 13:11.791
- My blade's got
a rough shape to it.

13:11.791 --> 13:14.127
<i>It's not terribly thin.</i>
<i>It's not terribly thick.</i>

13:14.127 --> 13:16.170
<i>So I feel like</i>
<i>I'm in pretty good shape,</i>

13:16.170 --> 13:18.172
<i>but I see some delams.</i>

13:18.172 --> 13:20.008
So I've got my quench
coming up,

13:20.008 --> 13:22.218
and I'm pretty concerned
about some delams.

13:22.218 --> 13:24.721
That could always cause it
to crack or warp.

13:24.721 --> 13:26.889
But I will turn in a knife.

13:26.889 --> 13:30.268
I will die before
I do not turn in a knife.

13:30.268 --> 13:32.603
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

13:32.603 --> 13:34.522
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:34.522 --> 13:37.817
- There we go, there's a
quench right there from Karl.

13:37.817 --> 13:39.485
<i>- It feels like</i>
<i>it's pretty good.</i>

13:39.485 --> 13:43.197
I don't hear a "tink."
I don't hear a crack.

13:43.197 --> 13:46.117
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:46.117 --> 13:48.036
- Looks like Tony
just quenched.

13:48.036 --> 13:49.996
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:49.996 --> 13:52.248
There you go, Derick quenched.

13:52.248 --> 13:54.542
<i>[rock music]</i>

13:54.542 --> 13:56.169
<i>- My blade is ugly.</i>

13:56.169 --> 13:58.212
<i>It's nowhere near</i>
<i>where I would like.</i>

13:58.212 --> 14:00.548
<i>I've got a little bit</i>
<i>of what looks like cold shuts</i>

14:00.548 --> 14:02.091
<i>along the top edge</i>
<i>and the bottom edge.</i>

14:02.091 --> 14:04.260
The top edge is that backside

14:04.260 --> 14:06.429
of that mild steel
from the canister.

14:06.429 --> 14:11.142
- Five minutes, blacksmiths!
Five minutes!

14:11.142 --> 14:12.810
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

14:12.810 --> 14:14.937
- I am definitely concerned
about the quench.

14:14.937 --> 14:17.899
<i>The clock is ticking</i>
<i>ridiculously fast.</i>

14:17.899 --> 14:19.358
<i>I'm feeling really,</i>
<i>really nervous.</i>

14:19.358 --> 14:21.235
You're a mother[bleep].

14:21.235 --> 14:24.072
I hope I have enough time.
I--it's going to be close.

14:24.072 --> 14:25.740
Really close.

14:25.740 --> 14:29.160
- Charlie, waiting until
the last three minutes

14:29.160 --> 14:31.245
to make this happen.

14:31.245 --> 14:33.790
- I have got to get this thing
into the quench.

14:33.790 --> 14:35.625
- Charlie's put himself
in a corner,

14:35.625 --> 14:37.251
because once he quenches,

14:37.251 --> 14:39.462
he's just going to be stuck
with what he gets.

14:39.462 --> 14:41.798
- 30 seconds!

14:41.798 --> 14:45.009
<i>- Would I like my blade</i>
<i>to be a whole lot better?</i>

14:45.009 --> 14:47.303
Hell yeah, but it is
what it is at this point.

14:47.303 --> 14:52.892
- 5, 4, 3, 2, 1.

14:52.892 --> 14:55.478
Bladesmiths, shut down your
machines, drop your tools.

14:55.478 --> 14:57.522
This round is over.

14:57.522 --> 14:59.732
<i>[rock music]</i>

14:59.732 --> 15:01.859
- It's really amazing
to be part of

15:01.859 --> 15:03.861
this invitational tournament
as a blacksmith.

15:03.861 --> 15:06.614
I think I have some issues
with the blade,

15:06.614 --> 15:08.574
but I also think
if I get to move forward,

15:08.574 --> 15:11.410
I've got enough meat
on that blade to correct them.

15:11.410 --> 15:13.287
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

15:13.287 --> 15:15.832
- All right, blacksmiths.
Now it's time for the judges

15:15.832 --> 15:18.000
to take a closer look
at your work.

15:18.000 --> 15:19.460
Derick, you're up first.

15:19.460 --> 15:21.420
Please present your blade
to the judges.

15:21.420 --> 15:23.714
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

15:23.714 --> 15:25.925
<i>- Well, Derick, I like</i>
<i>the shape you have here.</i>

15:25.925 --> 15:27.677
It's going to be
a good chopper.

15:27.677 --> 15:29.846
The one thing that gives me
the most pause, however,

15:29.846 --> 15:31.973
is the way you welded
those two cans together.

15:31.973 --> 15:34.225
The seam runs from the blade
to the spine,

15:34.225 --> 15:35.893
<i>right about at the place</i>

15:35.893 --> 15:38.020
<i>where most of the stress</i>
<i>is going to occur.</i>

15:38.020 --> 15:40.356
If this gets to testing,
I'm interested to see

15:40.356 --> 15:42.191
how it holds up at that spot.

15:42.191 --> 15:44.193
- Karl, you're up.

15:44.193 --> 15:45.987
Please present your blade
to the judges.

15:45.987 --> 15:48.156
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:48.156 --> 15:51.200
<i>- I like that shape.</i>
<i>It's solid for a chopper.</i>

15:51.200 --> 15:52.994
The only thing I worry about is

15:52.994 --> 15:56.414
there are some seams visible
along the spine.

15:56.414 --> 15:59.125
You know, the question is,
how deep do they go?

15:59.125 --> 16:01.002
- All right, Karl.
For a through tang,

16:01.002 --> 16:03.129
this almost looks
like a full tang.

16:03.129 --> 16:05.798
I wanted to see
a more defined through tang.

16:05.798 --> 16:07.800
But overall,
I like the way it looks.

16:07.800 --> 16:09.719
Good job.

16:09.719 --> 16:11.762
- Tony, please present
your work to the judges.

16:11.762 --> 16:14.098
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:14.098 --> 16:16.517
<i>- Well, Tony, on profile, I</i>
<i>like the shape that you have.</i>

16:16.517 --> 16:18.269
<i>But when you</i>
<i>look at it sideways,</i>

16:18.269 --> 16:21.147
it's as thick on the spine
as it is on the edge.

16:21.147 --> 16:24.150
That being said though,
it's a solid piece.

16:24.150 --> 16:26.152
- Thank you.
- Charlie, you're up.

16:26.152 --> 16:28.029
Please present your work
to the judges.

16:28.029 --> 16:29.614
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:29.614 --> 16:31.282
<i>- Well, Charlie, first off,</i>

16:31.282 --> 16:32.867
<i>this is a great shape</i>
<i>for a chopper.</i>

16:32.867 --> 16:34.702
I like that you dropped
the handle a little bit.

16:34.702 --> 16:36.495
But there's a cold shut.

16:36.495 --> 16:38.497
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:38.497 --> 16:42.251
And that's a dangerous place
to have mechanical issues.

16:42.251 --> 16:44.295
- Right up
the spine of the blade,

16:44.295 --> 16:46.589
I can see a seam
running this way,

16:46.589 --> 16:48.799
and again, a seam here.

16:48.799 --> 16:50.426
<i>I have a little bit of a worry</i>

16:50.426 --> 16:52.637
that that might
come popping loose

16:52.637 --> 16:54.263
when you
start grinding on this.

16:54.263 --> 16:56.766
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:56.766 --> 16:59.602
- Blacksmiths, the judges have
made their final decision.

16:59.602 --> 17:01.687
It's time for one of you
to leave the Forge.

17:01.687 --> 17:04.690
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

17:04.690 --> 17:06.567
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:06.567 --> 17:10.071
Charlie.
Your blade didn't make the cut.

17:10.071 --> 17:11.989
- Charlie, the multiple seams
in your blade,

17:11.989 --> 17:14.450
and that cold shut right
at the junction of your tang

17:14.450 --> 17:16.661
<i>could pose</i>
<i>a serious risk in testing.</i>

17:16.661 --> 17:18.496
That's why
we're letting you go.

17:18.496 --> 17:21.457
- Charlie, it's that time.
Please surrender your blade.

17:21.457 --> 17:23.459
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

17:23.459 --> 17:25.628
- I definitely didn't want to
go out in the first round.

17:25.628 --> 17:27.672
<i>I didn't want to go out</i>
<i>in the second round, either.</i>

17:27.672 --> 17:30.216
I wanted a spot
at the blacksmith's anvil.

17:30.216 --> 17:32.843
From here, I go back
to forging blades

17:32.843 --> 17:34.887
in my time,
and not in three hours.

17:34.887 --> 17:37.515
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:37.515 --> 17:39.392
- All right, blacksmiths.

17:39.392 --> 17:41.477
You've made it to the second
round of this competition,

17:41.477 --> 17:43.688
and now that your blades
have been tempered,

17:43.688 --> 17:45.690
it's time to turn them
into fully functional weapons

17:45.690 --> 17:47.900
by attaching handles to them.

17:47.900 --> 17:50.444
There's one more stipulation.

17:50.444 --> 17:53.447
You also need to fashion
and attach a pommel

17:53.447 --> 17:54.782
<i>to your through tang.</i>

17:54.782 --> 17:56.158
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:56.158 --> 17:58.828
At stake,
the blacksmith's anvil

17:58.828 --> 18:03.165
at our Tournament of Champions,
and ultimately, $50,000.

18:03.165 --> 18:07.044
Good luck, bladesmiths.
Your three hours starts now.

18:07.044 --> 18:09.255
<i>[rock music]</i>

18:09.255 --> 18:10.756
These guys not only have to

18:10.756 --> 18:13.009
address the flaws
in their blades.

18:13.009 --> 18:16.053
These blacksmiths also
have to fashion pommels.

18:16.053 --> 18:18.598
Now, we look at Karl's blade.

18:18.598 --> 18:21.934
He's got that
really wide through tang.

18:21.934 --> 18:24.520
So a lot of grinding
for that guy.

18:24.520 --> 18:27.732
- I need to start thinning
that down, reshaping it,

18:27.732 --> 18:29.150
<i>so that I can fit</i>

18:29.150 --> 18:31.319
a comfortable handle
on that blade.

18:31.319 --> 18:33.237
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:33.237 --> 18:36.490
- That tang has taken on
an entirely different shape.

18:36.490 --> 18:40.036
He's done a really good job
of thinning it out.

18:40.036 --> 18:42.163
<i>- Now it's time</i>
<i>to address the delam.</i>

18:42.163 --> 18:44.540
- His blade alone
has a lot of delaminations

18:44.540 --> 18:47.168
around the edge and the spine,
so grinding all that,

18:47.168 --> 18:48.669
and then finding out
what's underneath,

18:48.669 --> 18:50.129
he's got to be
very careful with that.

18:50.129 --> 18:52.173
<i>[rock music]</i>

18:52.173 --> 18:55.009
- My first task at hand is
to address some of the things

18:55.009 --> 18:56.677
that the judges
have pointed out.

18:56.677 --> 18:58.596
- Derick had kind of a seam
running down

18:58.596 --> 19:00.222
the middle of his blade.

19:00.222 --> 19:02.892
- The big problem I have
with this particular weld

19:02.892 --> 19:04.810
being in this place
on the knife.

19:04.810 --> 19:08.022
That makes it a weak spot.
- It would be a shame to see

19:08.022 --> 19:12.652
such great creativity
come undone in the testing.

19:12.652 --> 19:14.612
<i>- As soon as I get into</i>
<i>heavy grinding,</i>

19:14.612 --> 19:18.157
I'm seeing that the weld flaws
that the judges were seeing

19:18.157 --> 19:21.410
were actually just superficial.
Thank God.

19:21.410 --> 19:23.329
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:23.329 --> 19:25.414
- I'm starting out with
kind of a hollow grind.

19:25.414 --> 19:27.375
I just want to get that edge
down a little bit closer,

19:27.375 --> 19:29.251
and then
start working back from here,

19:29.251 --> 19:31.671
because I had a lot of meat
down the edge to get rid of.

19:31.671 --> 19:33.255
- Tony really needs
to turn that thing up

19:33.255 --> 19:35.049
if he wants to
take anything off.

19:35.049 --> 19:36.926
- I'm more concerned about

19:36.926 --> 19:39.845
making it through the brick
test than the belt slice.

19:39.845 --> 19:41.555
<i>That's why I want to leave</i>
<i>a thicker edge on it,</i>

19:41.555 --> 19:43.265
<i>more like an axe.</i>

19:43.265 --> 19:45.059
The thinner the edge,
the more likely that

19:45.059 --> 19:48.104
it's going to roll or chip.
- They've got two tests.

19:48.104 --> 19:50.773
They need to design for
both of them, not just one.

19:50.773 --> 19:53.818
- Hopefully, it holds up
so it'll still cut.

19:53.818 --> 19:56.862
- Blacksmiths,
you have two hours remaining

19:56.862 --> 19:58.531
until the weapons tests.

19:58.531 --> 20:00.157
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:00.157 --> 20:01.909
<i>- I do a lot of woodworking,</i>

20:01.909 --> 20:05.413
<i>so I'm familiar</i>
<i>with shaping wood.</i>

20:05.413 --> 20:07.707
- You've asked these smiths
to make a pommel.

20:07.707 --> 20:10.960
Definition is a protrusion
or a globe

20:10.960 --> 20:12.336
at the end of the handle.

20:12.336 --> 20:14.505
It's a counter-balance weight.

20:14.505 --> 20:16.340
<i>- I've got my handle on.</i>

20:16.340 --> 20:19.093
Now, I'm going to
put this pommel on.

20:19.093 --> 20:20.886
I've never really
done that before,

20:20.886 --> 20:23.639
so I'm a little shaky
on exactly how to do that.

20:23.639 --> 20:26.517
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

20:26.517 --> 20:27.727
- Looks like Derick
is making a guard

20:27.727 --> 20:29.603
out of the antler.

20:29.603 --> 20:32.189
- We didn't tell these guys
they had to make guards.

20:32.189 --> 20:34.400
- This antler is just going
to be shaped in a way

20:34.400 --> 20:35.776
that's going to keep your hand

20:35.776 --> 20:37.987
from sliding forward
onto the blade.

20:37.987 --> 20:40.030
- He definitely
has a piece of brass

20:40.030 --> 20:42.575
that's going to be big enough
to be considered a pommel.

20:42.575 --> 20:44.118
<i>- I'm feeling good.</i>

20:44.118 --> 20:45.286
<i>It's feeling like</i>
<i>I should be able</i>

20:45.286 --> 20:46.871
<i>to pull it off pretty quickly.</i>

20:46.871 --> 20:50.249
- 45 minutes remaining
to finish your work!

20:50.249 --> 20:52.460
<i>[rock music]</i>

20:52.460 --> 20:55.588
- I get the tang shaped
right about where I want it.

20:55.588 --> 20:57.798
I got to start
making the handle now.

20:57.798 --> 21:00.801
<i>And I grab this piece</i>
<i>of orange burl wood</i>

21:00.801 --> 21:02.928
<i>because I've</i>
<i>worked with it a lot.</i>

21:02.928 --> 21:06.182
Now, I'm trying to, as gently
as I can, kind of form fit it.

21:06.182 --> 21:07.767
[bleep]

21:07.767 --> 21:09.852
<i>But the handle's not fitting.</i>

21:09.852 --> 21:12.271
It's taking me longer
than I want it to,

21:12.271 --> 21:14.982
and the clock is still ticking.

21:14.982 --> 21:17.610
Well, I have to do something,
so I try banging on it.

21:17.610 --> 21:20.279
- Oh, no, no, no, no, no.
Tony, Tony, Tony, Tony.

21:20.279 --> 21:21.947
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

21:21.947 --> 21:23.949
- I'm giving it
a couple little love taps.

21:23.949 --> 21:26.452
- Tapping a handle into place
is a bad idea.

21:26.452 --> 21:28.287
- Burl, even though
it's stabilized,

21:28.287 --> 21:30.206
is still very brittle.

21:30.206 --> 21:32.291
- Can we not do that?

21:32.291 --> 21:34.585
- I just have a little bit
further to go.

21:38.422 --> 21:41.383
- I've got the handle
so close to where I want it.

21:41.383 --> 21:43.636
- It doesn't matter how tough
your handle material is.

21:43.636 --> 21:45.471
You can't hammer it on there.

21:45.471 --> 21:46.764
[wood cracks]

21:46.764 --> 21:48.766
- Son of a [bleep].

21:48.766 --> 21:51.894
There's a significant crack
in it.

21:51.894 --> 21:54.980
- So now, Tony has to
start over on this handle.

21:54.980 --> 21:57.817
<i>- Grabbed the micarta,</i>
<i>I can start drilling.</i>

21:57.817 --> 21:59.735
I don't know if I can
get this done or not.

21:59.735 --> 22:02.154
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:02.154 --> 22:03.781
<i>- It's 38 minutes,</i>
<i>four seconds.</i>

22:03.781 --> 22:05.783
Definitely some pressure.

22:05.783 --> 22:09.161
<i>- I finally finish</i>
<i>my fine-tuning on the handle.</i>

22:09.161 --> 22:11.080
- For the test,
we know we're going to

22:11.080 --> 22:13.082
chop on a fire brick,

22:13.082 --> 22:18.087
<i>so I've got to put a pretty</i>
<i>hefty edge on this thing.</i>

22:18.087 --> 22:20.005
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:20.005 --> 22:21.924
<i>- So I've finally</i>
<i>got everything sorted out,</i>

22:21.924 --> 22:24.343
and I'm thinking,
with my last 15 minutes,

22:24.343 --> 22:25.761
<i>let's etch this blade.</i>

22:25.761 --> 22:28.097
Let's see if I do have anything

22:28.097 --> 22:30.641
<i>that I can't see</i>
<i>as far as delams.</i>

22:30.641 --> 22:34.103
A cooler pattern than I
expected it to be, hell yeah.

22:34.103 --> 22:35.563
- So the acid that we have

22:35.563 --> 22:38.023
in our acid baths
is ferric chloride.

22:38.023 --> 22:40.192
- Yeah, so if you
dip the steel into the acid,

22:40.192 --> 22:42.820
the hardened steel gets black,
and then, the back of the steel

22:42.820 --> 22:44.989
gets just sort of grey.
- Okay.

22:44.989 --> 22:47.199
<i>- I am extremely worried</i>

22:47.199 --> 22:49.451
<i>that I'm not</i>
<i>going to be able to finish.</i>

22:49.451 --> 22:52.663
I'm [bleep] bricks right now,
with looking at the clock.

22:52.663 --> 22:55.791
<i>I've never put a pommel on,</i>
<i>so this is a first for me.</i>

22:55.791 --> 22:58.836
<i>I got to get this handle</i>
<i>shaped, and get it sharpened.</i>

22:58.836 --> 23:01.046
I head over to the grinder,
and I'm jumping between

23:01.046 --> 23:04.466
<i>the blade and handle,</i>
<i>blade and handle.</i>

23:04.466 --> 23:08.971
<i>Trying to produce something</i>
<i>that will work.</i>

23:08.971 --> 23:14.059
- 5, 4, 3, 2, 1.

23:14.059 --> 23:16.854
Blacksmiths, drop your tools.

23:16.854 --> 23:19.732
This round is over.

23:19.732 --> 23:23.527
- I didn't have time to get
the edge I want on it,

23:23.527 --> 23:26.697
but I still feel
that I have a chance.

23:26.697 --> 23:29.033
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

23:29.033 --> 23:31.660
- Hello, blacksmiths.
Welcome to the strength test.

23:31.660 --> 23:33.412
To test the strength
of your edge,

23:33.412 --> 23:35.706
as well as the overall
construction of your knives,

23:35.706 --> 23:37.666
I'm going to bash them
into these firebricks.

23:37.666 --> 23:38.959
Remember,
this test is all about

23:38.959 --> 23:40.502
what the bricks
do to your knives,

23:40.502 --> 23:42.796
and not what the knives
do to the bricks.

23:42.796 --> 23:43.881
Derick, you're up first.
You ready?

23:43.881 --> 23:46.967
- Sure, why not?

23:46.967 --> 23:49.303
<i>All the judges seemed</i>
<i>to have been worried about</i>

23:49.303 --> 23:52.056
<i>the seams</i>
<i>where the blocks joined.</i>

23:52.056 --> 23:54.683
<i>This thing could break in half</i>
<i>as soon as he hits it.</i>

23:54.683 --> 23:56.101
[exhales]

23:56.101 --> 23:58.354
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

23:58.354 --> 24:01.440
<i>[rock music]</i>

24:01.440 --> 24:08.322
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:15.079 --> 24:17.081
- Well, Derick,
most importantly,

24:17.081 --> 24:19.416
your forge weld
held up perfect.

24:19.416 --> 24:20.834
I like the feeling
of your handle,

24:20.834 --> 24:22.378
and the weight is good.

24:22.378 --> 24:26.090
But, uh, you now have
a serrated blade.

24:26.090 --> 24:29.009
The fire bricks did some
chipping on your blade here.

24:29.009 --> 24:32.012
Karl, are you ready?
- 100 percent.

24:32.012 --> 24:34.974
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

24:34.974 --> 24:36.392
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:36.392 --> 24:38.852
[exhales]

24:38.852 --> 24:41.438
Just do it slow.
- Slow and easy?

24:41.438 --> 24:43.565
[laughter]

24:43.565 --> 24:45.275
That's not happening.

24:45.275 --> 24:47.695
- [laughs]
[clears throat]

24:47.695 --> 24:49.989
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

24:49.989 --> 24:52.992
<i>[rock music]</i>

24:52.992 --> 24:59.873
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:04.336 --> 25:06.964
- [exhales]

25:06.964 --> 25:09.508
- Well, Karl,
I like the weight of it.

25:09.508 --> 25:12.219
There is some chipping and
rolling at the edge here.

25:12.219 --> 25:14.513
<i>You now have</i>
<i>a serrated blade as well.</i>

25:14.513 --> 25:16.640
Everything held up,
it's all tight.

25:16.640 --> 25:18.934
There's nothing
came loose on it, well done.

25:18.934 --> 25:22.062
- Thank you.
- Tony, what are you thinking?

25:22.062 --> 25:24.690
- Tear it up.

25:24.690 --> 25:28.318
<i>I see Derick's</i>
<i>and Karl's blades damaged.</i>

25:28.318 --> 25:30.487
Now, I'm feeling
really confident,

25:30.487 --> 25:33.198
<i>because I know my blade</i>
<i>has some good heft to it.</i>

25:33.198 --> 25:36.326
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

25:36.326 --> 25:39.288
<i>[rock music]</i>

25:39.288 --> 25:45.377
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:48.505 --> 25:51.341
<i>[rock music resumes]</i>

25:57.389 --> 25:59.349
- Dude.

25:59.349 --> 26:01.685
<i>[tense music]</i>

26:01.685 --> 26:04.688
- Well, Tony,
your edge held up pretty well.

26:04.688 --> 26:06.732
But that's to be expected.

26:06.732 --> 26:08.650
There's so much mass
in this thing.

26:08.650 --> 26:10.444
There is some
edge deflection here,

26:10.444 --> 26:12.321
and a little chipping,
but not too much.

26:12.321 --> 26:15.199
Just because it is
such a stout, stout blade.

26:15.199 --> 26:17.993
But everything is still tight.
Well done.

26:17.993 --> 26:21.038
- Thank you.

26:21.038 --> 26:22.623
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

26:22.623 --> 26:24.958
- Blacksmiths,
to find out if your blades

26:24.958 --> 26:26.919
are still sharp,
I will take your weapon,

26:26.919 --> 26:29.296
and slash across
these grinder belts.

26:29.296 --> 26:31.131
You will need a sharp edge.

26:31.131 --> 26:33.383
Derick, you're up first.
You ready?

26:33.383 --> 26:35.052
- Sure, let's do it.

26:35.052 --> 26:38.013
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

26:38.013 --> 26:44.394
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:44.394 --> 26:47.439
<i>[rock music]</i>

26:47.439 --> 26:52.027
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:52.027 --> 26:54.196
<i>[tense music]</i>

26:54.196 --> 26:56.490
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:56.490 --> 26:59.618
- All right, Derick, there's
a lot of rolled edges in here.

26:59.618 --> 27:01.245
It's sharp enough
to cut through the first,

27:01.245 --> 27:03.122
and a little bit
of the second belt,

27:03.122 --> 27:05.082
but it did not cut the rest.

27:05.082 --> 27:09.002
So, your blade, sir, will cut.
A little.

27:09.002 --> 27:10.379
- Ha.
- All right, Karl.

27:10.379 --> 27:12.005
You're up next.
You ready?

27:12.005 --> 27:14.049
- 100 percent.
- Let's do this.

27:14.049 --> 27:17.052
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

27:17.052 --> 27:23.934
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:25.936 --> 27:27.855
- [exhales]

27:27.855 --> 27:29.857
<i>[tense music]</i>

27:29.857 --> 27:31.316
- All right, Karl.

27:31.316 --> 27:33.193
During the test
with those bricks,

27:33.193 --> 27:35.112
it dulled the edges.

27:35.112 --> 27:38.532
And slashing with that,
it cut even less

27:38.532 --> 27:40.200
on the first belt.

27:40.200 --> 27:43.996
Overall, sir,
your blade will cut even less.

27:43.996 --> 27:45.664
- [groans]

27:45.664 --> 27:46.915
- All right, Tony,
it's your turn.

27:46.915 --> 27:48.375
- You ready?
- Tear it up.

27:52.212 --> 27:53.755
<i>- Going into the slice test,</i>

27:53.755 --> 27:55.507
<i>I feel pretty good</i>
<i>about my chances</i>

27:55.507 --> 27:57.676
because of the sheer weight.

27:57.676 --> 27:59.887
<i>I'm thinking he's going to</i>
<i>blow through all of them.</i>

27:59.887 --> 28:02.931
<i>[rock music]</i>

28:02.931 --> 28:09.813
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:13.233 --> 28:16.194
<i>[tense music]</i>

28:16.194 --> 28:17.738
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:17.738 --> 28:19.406
- Well, Tony,
I was really concerned

28:19.406 --> 28:20.699
watching your edge earlier.

28:20.699 --> 28:22.951
How thick it is,
like an axe head.

28:22.951 --> 28:26.413
That coupled with testing this
on the bricks earlier

28:26.413 --> 28:28.749
really took out all the edges
that you had there.

28:28.749 --> 28:30.584
It just bounced off.

28:30.584 --> 28:34.796
So unfortunately, Tony,
your blade will not cut.

28:34.796 --> 28:36.757
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

28:36.757 --> 28:39.676
- Blacksmiths, the judges
have made their final decision.

28:39.676 --> 28:42.554
For one of you, the road to
the Tournament of Champions

28:42.554 --> 28:44.640
and $50,000 ends right here.

28:44.640 --> 28:48.602
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:48.602 --> 28:53.523
Tony.
Your blade didn't make the cut.

28:53.523 --> 28:56.401
- Tony, while every blade
took some damage

28:56.401 --> 28:57.986
in a very grueling
strength test,

28:57.986 --> 28:59.988
<i>the obtuse edge</i>
<i>you put on yours</i>

28:59.988 --> 29:01.657
<i>made it so it didn't cut,</i>

29:01.657 --> 29:04.201
and it's for that reason
we're sending you home.

29:04.201 --> 29:05.869
- Yeah, understood.

29:05.869 --> 29:07.871
- Tony, please surrender
your blade.

29:07.871 --> 29:09.581
<i>[somber music]</i>

29:09.581 --> 29:12.626
- I feel like I represented
blacksmiths well.

29:12.626 --> 29:14.503
<i>I accomplished some tasks</i>

29:14.503 --> 29:17.547
that were virtually impossible
in very little time,

29:17.547 --> 29:19.925
<i>and I feel like I'm going home</i>
<i>a winner no matter what.</i>

29:19.925 --> 29:23.887
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:23.887 --> 29:26.014
- Derick, Karl,
congratulations.

29:26.014 --> 29:27.057
You've both made it into
the third round

29:27.057 --> 29:28.850
of this competition.

29:28.850 --> 29:30.686
Now, we're sending you back
to your home forges

29:30.686 --> 29:33.313
to work on a iconic weapon
from history.

29:33.313 --> 29:34.940
That weapon is...

29:34.940 --> 29:37.943
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

29:37.943 --> 29:39.319
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:39.319 --> 29:42.030
The knightly poleaxe.

29:42.030 --> 29:43.782
- [chuckles]
- [exhales]

29:43.782 --> 29:46.034
<i>- The favorite weapon</i>
<i>of European knights</i>

29:46.034 --> 29:48.286
<i>from the 14th</i>
<i>through 16th centuries,</i>

29:48.286 --> 29:49.621
<i>the knightly poleaxe</i>
<i>was a versatile</i>

29:49.621 --> 29:51.665
<i>and brutal tool of war.</i>

29:51.665 --> 29:53.834
<i>It's multi-part construction</i>
<i>featured an axe blade,</i>

29:53.834 --> 29:57.087
<i>hammer head, and a spike</i>
<i>mounted to a long shaft.</i>

29:57.087 --> 29:59.756
<i>It was ideal for combat</i>
<i>against armor-clad opponents,</i>

29:59.756 --> 30:01.466
<i>allowing knights</i>
<i>to keep their distance</i>

30:01.466 --> 30:02.884
<i>while delivering</i>
<i>deadly strikes</i>

30:02.884 --> 30:05.262
<i>that could crush</i>
<i>and pierce armor.</i>

30:05.262 --> 30:07.222
<i>Although poleaxes</i>
<i>faded from the battlefield</i>

30:07.222 --> 30:09.433
<i>by the 18th century,</i>
<i>it still remains</i>

30:09.433 --> 30:11.476
<i>one of the most iconic</i>
<i>multi-purpose weapons</i>

30:11.476 --> 30:13.061
<i>of the medieval era.</i>

30:13.061 --> 30:14.855
<i>Today, players</i>
<i>can wield the weapon</i>

30:14.855 --> 30:18.025
<i>in the game "For Honor."</i>

30:18.025 --> 30:21.111
Your weapons must fall within
the following parameters.

30:21.111 --> 30:24.823
You must include a top spike,
an axe, a hammerhead,

30:24.823 --> 30:27.617
and langets on both sides
of the shaft,

30:27.617 --> 30:30.787
as well as a guard
below the langets.

30:30.787 --> 30:34.082
<i>- It's got a spike on the top,</i>
<i>and a blade on the front,</i>

30:34.082 --> 30:35.500
<i>and a hammer on the back.</i>

30:35.500 --> 30:38.170
How in the hell
am I going to be able

30:38.170 --> 30:40.422
to put this thing together?

30:40.422 --> 30:42.924
<i>It's got me</i>
<i>a little concerned.</i>

30:42.924 --> 30:44.843
- You will have five days
at your home forge

30:44.843 --> 30:46.428
to complete this challenge.

30:46.428 --> 30:48.388
After five days,
you'll be presenting them

30:48.388 --> 30:49.931
to our panel of expert judges.

30:49.931 --> 30:52.017
And only after they've
thoroughly tested them

30:52.017 --> 30:54.603
will they declare one of you
the "Forged in Fire" champion

30:54.603 --> 30:56.354
for the blacksmith class,

30:56.354 --> 30:59.316
and send you on
to the Tournament of Champions.

30:59.316 --> 31:02.152
Good luck, blacksmiths.
We'll see you in five days.

31:02.152 --> 31:04.821
<i>[rock music]</i>

31:04.821 --> 31:06.239
<i>- I love this shop.</i>

31:06.239 --> 31:08.116
This place is like
my sanctuary.

31:08.116 --> 31:10.952
<i>Working in a traditional</i>
<i>fashion is important to me</i>

31:10.952 --> 31:12.871
<i>to perpetuate this craft.</i>

31:12.871 --> 31:14.873
As a blacksmith,
you have to make tools

31:14.873 --> 31:16.750
to accomplish the task at hand.

31:16.750 --> 31:20.087
<i>So I will be producing</i>
<i>some tools for this job.</i>

31:20.087 --> 31:22.756
<i>With the poleaxe,</i>
<i>creating an eye</i>

31:22.756 --> 31:24.716
<i>without using</i>
<i>a milling machine</i>

31:24.716 --> 31:28.136
or some other modern method
is very challenging.

31:28.136 --> 31:30.222
<i>But I'm a blacksmith.</i>

31:30.222 --> 31:33.225
I'm going to do it how
a blacksmith should do it.

31:33.225 --> 31:34.935
<i>Today, I got three tools done.</i>

31:34.935 --> 31:37.145
<i>The punch</i>
<i>for creating the hole.</i>

31:37.145 --> 31:41.274
<i>The drift for making the hole</i>
<i>the correct size and shape.</i>

31:41.274 --> 31:44.402
<i>I also made the dice that's</i>
<i>going to help me create</i>

31:44.402 --> 31:46.404
<i>the shape that is</i>
<i>going to be the hammer.</i>

31:46.404 --> 31:49.407
<i>[rock music]</i>

31:49.407 --> 31:51.326
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:51.326 --> 31:53.620
- The poleaxe was kind of
three weapons in one,

31:53.620 --> 31:55.288
<i>and it's at the end</i>
<i>of a long stick,</i>

31:55.288 --> 31:57.290
so it's going
to be a challenge.

31:57.290 --> 31:59.709
<i>I don't have a power hammer.</i>
<i>I don't have a press.</i>

31:59.709 --> 32:02.254
<i>I'm going to have to be</i>
<i>a little more creative</i>

32:02.254 --> 32:04.005
in how I put it together,

32:04.005 --> 32:05.632
<i>rather than just try</i>
<i>to beat it out</i>

32:05.632 --> 32:07.008
<i>of a single piece of steel.</i>

32:07.008 --> 32:08.426
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:08.426 --> 32:11.221
<i>The two pieces of 7-inch 5160,</i>

32:11.221 --> 32:13.849
<i>I'm going to try</i>
<i>to forge-weld those together,</i>

32:13.849 --> 32:16.268
<i>then draw that out to be</i>
<i>the face of my axe.</i>

32:16.268 --> 32:18.145
I'm going to let it cool off,

32:18.145 --> 32:20.438
and then, uh,
I'm trying to break it.

32:20.438 --> 32:24.276
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:24.276 --> 32:26.153
I'm happy.

32:26.153 --> 32:28.488
<i>[rock music]</i>

32:28.488 --> 32:30.198
<i>- The most critical part</i>
<i>of today</i>

32:30.198 --> 32:32.159
<i>is getting the hole correct.</i>

32:32.159 --> 32:35.245
<i>If it's too small, your</i>
<i>handle's going to break off.</i>

32:35.245 --> 32:36.705
<i>If it's too large,</i>
<i>it's going to be</i>

32:36.705 --> 32:38.456
<i>too cumbersome and too heavy.</i>

32:38.456 --> 32:41.293
At this point, I can move
to drawing out the axe.

32:41.293 --> 32:43.545
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

32:43.545 --> 32:44.754
<i>I'm finding that I'm</i>
<i>coming a little short</i>

32:44.754 --> 32:46.381
<i>on material here.</i>

32:46.381 --> 32:47.924
What I'm going to do
is I'm going to have this

32:47.924 --> 32:50.260
curved in a little bit more
than it is,

32:50.260 --> 32:53.763
<i>so that as I forge this</i>
<i>thickness out, it'll spread,</i>

32:53.763 --> 32:56.892
<i>and force these</i>
<i>into a nice fan shape.</i>

32:56.892 --> 32:58.560
And that, folks, is an axe.

32:58.560 --> 33:00.770
<i>[rock music]</i>

33:00.770 --> 33:04.983
<i>- Day three, going to start</i>
<i>working on the wood shafts.</i>

33:04.983 --> 33:07.694
<i>Cutting this in half</i>
<i>will allow me</i>

33:07.694 --> 33:10.488
to put a groove
in the top and the bottom

33:10.488 --> 33:13.033
<i>to accept the pommel</i>
<i>and the spike.</i>

33:13.033 --> 33:15.493
I could take those things
and beat them against a wall

33:15.493 --> 33:17.954
all day long,
and I doubt they'd break.

33:17.954 --> 33:21.750
Welding up
the face of the hammer.

33:21.750 --> 33:25.170
The blacksmith world doesn't
want me to weld this on.

33:25.170 --> 33:29.716
To hide the weld, I'm going
to put it inside the H here.

33:29.716 --> 33:32.177
It's sacrificing authenticity,

33:32.177 --> 33:35.222
<i>but a modern blacksmith</i>
<i>uses all the modern tools,</i>

33:35.222 --> 33:36.640
<i>and a welder is a modern tool.</i>

33:36.640 --> 33:38.308
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

33:38.308 --> 33:39.434
<i>- The bottom of that</i>
<i>is actually a</i>

33:39.434 --> 33:41.519
<i>perfect temperature right now.</i>

33:41.519 --> 33:45.398
<i>I'm going to put just the end</i>
<i>of this thing in here.</i>

33:45.398 --> 33:48.860
<i>I'm going to harden the head.</i>
<i>If this goes wrong,</i>

33:48.860 --> 33:51.529
<i>I definitely don't have enough</i>
<i>time to make another one.</i>

33:51.529 --> 33:53.531
<i>It's this or nothing.</i>

33:53.531 --> 33:54.991
Oh, yeah.

33:54.991 --> 33:56.326
[metal tings]

33:56.326 --> 33:57.702
She's hard as can be.

33:57.702 --> 33:59.329
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

33:59.329 --> 34:01.831
<i>- I'm starting to assemble.</i>

34:01.831 --> 34:04.668
<i>The first thing I do is put</i>
<i>the head on, tighten it down.</i>

34:04.668 --> 34:06.878
<i>I mean, that thing's</i>
<i>not going anywhere.</i>

34:06.878 --> 34:10.382
<i>And I put the langets on.</i>
<i>Everything's fine.</i>

34:10.382 --> 34:12.425
I'm moving right along here.

34:12.425 --> 34:14.636
<i>And I hear a "kink."</i>

34:14.636 --> 34:16.471
Oh, damn.

34:16.471 --> 34:18.139
<i>[tense music]</i>

34:18.139 --> 34:19.266
<i>There's a crack.</i>

34:19.266 --> 34:20.976
Oh!

34:20.976 --> 34:22.686
<i>And the pommel's loose.</i>

34:22.686 --> 34:24.813
Damn.

34:24.813 --> 34:27.983
Man, "Forged in Fire"
bites your ass in again.

34:27.983 --> 34:29.734
<i>And I come up with a solution.</i>

34:29.734 --> 34:32.404
<i>It's not the best,</i>
<i>but it's a solution.</i>

34:32.404 --> 34:33.947
<i>I have to fix the nail,</i>

34:33.947 --> 34:35.365
<i>I have to peen</i>
<i>over the pommel,</i>

34:35.365 --> 34:37.701
and it's like,
I'm running out of time.

34:37.701 --> 34:39.577
Wish me luck.

34:39.577 --> 34:41.746
That is ugly!

34:41.746 --> 34:43.999
<i>[rock music]</i>

34:43.999 --> 34:46.626
<i>- This is my final assembly.</i>

34:46.626 --> 34:49.671
<i>There's no glue in this</i>
<i>fit up whatsoever.</i>

34:49.671 --> 34:51.548
<i>The best part about</i>
<i>making something like this</i>

34:51.548 --> 34:52.757
<i>is testing it.</i>

34:52.757 --> 34:55.051
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:55.051 --> 34:56.845
Holy [bleep].

34:56.845 --> 34:59.180
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:59.180 --> 35:01.057
Aw, [bleep].

35:05.020 --> 35:07.314
<i>I just</i>
- Aw, [bleep].

35:07.314 --> 35:10.317
<i>I just broke my weapon</i>
<i>with almost no time to spare.</i>

35:10.317 --> 35:12.485
All right, got the spike.

35:12.485 --> 35:15.614
I'm going to go,
uh, do some magic.

35:15.614 --> 35:18.116
<i>I'm really hoping</i>
<i>that this arc weld</i>

35:18.116 --> 35:20.493
<i>is going to be stronger</i>
<i>than what I had before.</i>

35:20.493 --> 35:22.912
I started arc welding a grand
total of three weeks ago.

35:22.912 --> 35:24.039
I just don't know
that everything's

35:24.039 --> 35:25.999
going to hold together.

35:25.999 --> 35:27.959
This could be the difference
between winning and losing.

35:27.959 --> 35:30.879
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

35:30.879 --> 35:33.590
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:33.590 --> 35:36.009
- Derick, Karl,
welcome back to the Forge.

35:36.009 --> 35:38.511
You blacksmiths
have had five days

35:38.511 --> 35:40.347
at your home forges
to personalize

35:40.347 --> 35:42.474
your knightly poleaxes.

35:42.474 --> 35:43.892
Derick, how did it go for you?

35:43.892 --> 35:45.477
- I decided to go
as traditional

35:45.477 --> 35:47.604
as I possibly could with this.

35:47.604 --> 35:52.317
<i>The hammer and axe is W1,</i>
<i>the spike is 1084,</i>

35:52.317 --> 35:54.653
<i>and all the other parts</i>
<i>are wrought iron.</i>

35:54.653 --> 35:56.613
It's freaking evil.
I love it.

35:56.613 --> 35:58.531
- And you, Karl?
- All the metal parts

35:58.531 --> 36:00.533
are made from 5160.

36:00.533 --> 36:03.703
<i>Copper accents,</i>
<i>the guard is handspun,</i>

36:03.703 --> 36:07.707
<i>and the pommel was cast</i>
<i>from recycled copper.</i>

36:07.707 --> 36:10.627
- All right, gentleman,
to determine which of you

36:10.627 --> 36:12.295
is our "Forged in Fire"
champion

36:12.295 --> 36:14.589
for the blacksmiths class,
the judges will now

36:14.589 --> 36:16.633
put your weapons through
a series of three tests.

36:16.633 --> 36:18.593
There will be a strength test,
a sharpness test,

36:18.593 --> 36:20.970
and up first, Doug's kill test.

36:20.970 --> 36:22.472
- Yeah.
- Yes.

36:22.472 --> 36:25.350
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

36:25.350 --> 36:27.727
- Blacksmiths, to find out
what kind of lethal damage

36:27.727 --> 36:30.605
your poleaxe will do,
I will take your poleaxe

36:30.605 --> 36:33.900
and deliver mayhem
on this ballistics dummy.

36:33.900 --> 36:35.652
Derick, you're up first.
You ready?

36:35.652 --> 36:36.903
- Oh, yeah.
- Let's do this.

36:36.903 --> 36:38.905
- Good luck.

36:38.905 --> 36:41.741
<i>- I'm really excited to see</i>
<i>how this thing cuts.</i>

36:41.741 --> 36:45.286
The blacksmith's anvil is
at stake here, and I want it.

36:45.286 --> 36:48.206
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

36:48.206 --> 36:50.458
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:50.458 --> 36:51.835
- [exhales]

36:52.794 --> 36:59.718
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:04.723 --> 37:07.225
Oh, my God.

37:07.225 --> 37:09.477
Yeah.
- All right, Derick.

37:09.477 --> 37:12.063
You want to know what kind
of carnage it will do?

37:12.063 --> 37:14.858
There you go.

37:14.858 --> 37:18.987
Your axe is sharp,
and your spike here

37:18.987 --> 37:21.156
penetrated with every thrust.

37:21.156 --> 37:24.325
So your weapon, sir, will kill.

37:24.325 --> 37:26.703
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

37:26.703 --> 37:28.079
- All right, Karl,
it's your turn.

37:28.079 --> 37:29.873
You ready?
- 100 percent.

37:29.873 --> 37:31.374
- Let's do this.

37:31.374 --> 37:34.335
- I hope mine can perform
as well as that.

37:34.335 --> 37:37.172
The thing you live for
is "it will kill."

37:37.172 --> 37:40.175
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

37:40.175 --> 37:43.178
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:43.178 --> 37:44.179
[exhales]

37:44.179 --> 37:51.102
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:00.111 --> 38:01.738
[exhales]

38:01.738 --> 38:03.239
- All right, Karl.

38:03.239 --> 38:05.116
Your hammerhead
definitely crushes,

38:05.116 --> 38:06.534
and goes right into that,

38:06.534 --> 38:09.078
breaking the sternum
and the ribs.

38:09.078 --> 38:12.582
Your axe here is sharp.
Here's the issue.

38:12.582 --> 38:14.375
It's so top-heavy.

38:14.375 --> 38:16.211
When you're coming forward,
well and good,

38:16.211 --> 38:19.422
but the recovery feels like
I'm wasting energy.

38:19.422 --> 38:24.052
Overall, though, your weapon
will destruct and kill.

38:24.052 --> 38:26.471
- [laughs]

38:26.471 --> 38:27.972
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

38:27.972 --> 38:29.641
- All right, gentleman.
What I'll do

38:29.641 --> 38:31.559
to test the strength
of your blades

38:31.559 --> 38:33.770
is try to break through
that door.

38:33.770 --> 38:37.524
Now, this test is not about
what your axes do to this door,

38:37.524 --> 38:39.462
but what this door
does to your axes.

38:43.342 --> 38:44.686
- Derick, you're up first.
You ready?

38:44.686 --> 38:47.022
- All right, let's get weird.

38:47.022 --> 38:50.066
I'm expecting to see my spike
fly across the shop.

38:50.066 --> 38:52.569
The spike's the tripping point
that could send me home.

38:52.569 --> 38:55.447
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

38:55.447 --> 38:58.325
<i>[rock music]</i>

38:58.325 --> 39:05.248
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:08.293 --> 39:10.503
[laughs]

39:10.503 --> 39:13.506
<i>[tense music]</i>

39:13.506 --> 39:15.759
- There is, uh--

39:15.759 --> 39:16.843
there's not a mark on this.

39:16.843 --> 39:17.928
[laughs]

39:17.928 --> 39:19.930
- Okay.

39:19.930 --> 39:23.725
- Just, no damage, no rolling.
Everything's still tight.

39:23.725 --> 39:26.144
It's a strong weapon.
Nicely done, good job.

39:26.144 --> 39:28.772
- Awesome, thank you.
- All right, Karl.

39:28.772 --> 39:30.398
Your turn, you ready?
- 100 percent.

39:30.398 --> 39:31.942
- Okay.

39:31.942 --> 39:34.903
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

39:34.903 --> 39:38.573
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:38.573 --> 39:41.534
<i>[rock music]</i>

39:41.534 --> 39:48.416
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:54.089 --> 39:56.758
<i>[tense music]</i>

39:56.758 --> 39:58.510
- Okay, Karl, before I
pass this off to Doug

39:58.510 --> 40:00.887
for a sharpness test,
I have some questions

40:00.887 --> 40:02.514
about the construction
of this head.

40:02.514 --> 40:04.808
- Okay.
- Was this a solid piece

40:04.808 --> 40:06.601
going from this side
to this side?

40:06.601 --> 40:08.478
- No, it's mid-welded

40:08.478 --> 40:11.898
to the tang of the spear
on the inside.

40:11.898 --> 40:13.775
- You mean the hammerhead
is mid-welded on?

40:13.775 --> 40:16.152
- Correct.
- So this means

40:16.152 --> 40:19.614
that that mid weld
has broken, because--

40:19.614 --> 40:22.701
okay, that's what I
didn't want to have happen.

40:22.701 --> 40:24.911
Um...

40:24.911 --> 40:27.914
<i>[tense music]</i>

40:27.914 --> 40:31.084
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:31.084 --> 40:34.713
- Karl, unfortunately,
your weapon has suffered

40:34.713 --> 40:37.340
a catastrophic failure in the
middle of our strength test,

40:37.340 --> 40:39.342
and can no longer
be tested safely.

40:39.342 --> 40:41.428
For that reason,
I have to ask you

40:41.428 --> 40:44.681
to please leave the Forge.
- Thank you.

40:44.681 --> 40:47.058
Good luck, man.

40:47.058 --> 40:50.478
<i>I'm disappointed.</i>
<i>I'm a very competitive person.</i>

40:50.478 --> 40:56.067
But I have absolutely,
100 percent, zero regrets.

40:56.067 --> 40:58.820
<i>The whole idea for me is,</i>
<i>I wanted to see</i>

40:58.820 --> 41:01.323
<i>what I could do, and how far</i>
<i>I could push myself.</i>

41:01.323 --> 41:02.991
First thing I'm going to do
when I get home.

41:02.991 --> 41:05.452
Going to kiss my wife,
have an adult beverage,

41:05.452 --> 41:07.162
<i>and think about</i>
<i>what the next project is.</i>

41:07.162 --> 41:09.205
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:09.205 --> 41:10.915
- Derick, congratulations.

41:10.915 --> 41:12.751
<i>You are the</i>
<i>"Forged in Fire" champion</i>

41:12.751 --> 41:14.461
<i>for the blacksmith class.</i>

41:14.461 --> 41:15.837
<i>We're going to be</i>
<i>moving you forward into</i>

41:15.837 --> 41:17.380
<i>our Tournament of Champions,</i>

41:17.380 --> 41:19.883
<i>where you'll compete</i>
<i>for $50,000</i>

41:19.883 --> 41:22.427
and the title
of Tournament Champion.

41:22.427 --> 41:23.845
How you feeling right now?

41:23.845 --> 41:25.513
- It's weird, man.
It's real weird.

41:25.513 --> 41:27.599
- [laughs]

41:27.599 --> 41:29.267
<i>- I'm super stoked right now.</i>

41:29.267 --> 41:31.186
<i>[laughs]</i>

41:31.186 --> 41:32.812
It feels really good
to represent

41:32.812 --> 41:34.481
for the blacksmith's anvil.

41:34.481 --> 41:35.857
<i>It's going to be</i>
<i>freaking awesome.</i>

41:35.857 --> 41:37.525
Other smiths better watch out,

41:37.525 --> 41:39.235
'cause the blacksmiths
are coming.

41:39.235 --> 41:42.197
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

41:42.197 --> 41:44.407
<i>♪ ♪</i>
